+ Threat Entity Database Entry

[[size large]]**Threat ID:**[[/size]]

**NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca -- "Village Jeweler"**

[[size large]]**Authorized Response Level:**[[/size]]
[[size 0%]][[/size]]
##red|[[size 250%]] 0 [[/size]]## **(In Storage, Cooperative)**

[[size large]]**Description:**[[/size]]

[[include :scp-wiki:component:image-block-peppo
| name=engine.jpg
| caption=NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca, Module 2, photographed 1953.
| width=35%
| align=right]]

NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca is an electro-thaumic analytical engine powered by the captured spirit of English polymath Charles Babbage (1791-1871), renowned mathematician, engineer and economist. The physical framework of NTE-2858 is believed to be an advanced mechanical prototype, commenced in 1863 and linked with Babbage's consciousness following his physical death.

NTE-2858 has two processing modules, each comprised of exactly 4,000 components, for a combined weight of five tons. When fully assembled, these modules are 2.1 meters tall, 3.4 meters long, and 45.7 centimeters deep (7 feet by 11 feet by 18 inches).

NTE-2858's third module is a standing brass wheel, 45.7 centimeters (18 inches) in diameter, fitted with an ectoplasmic containment vessel. NTE-2858 communicates by spinning rotary dials inscribed with the full Latin alphabet (including various modifiers), Arabic numerals, punctuation, and mathematical operators. This mode of articulation is similar to a seance conducted with spirit board and planchette; however, NTE-2858 is capable of detecting auditory stimuli and does not require a living interpreter.

NTE-2858 communicates at an average of 6-10 characters per second (72-120 words per minute, or 360-600 RPM), which is difficult for the average observer to understand. To compensate, project engineers fitted NTE-2858's dialing system with cylindrical typewheels, which parse raw output into printed words.

When the articulation terminal is physically linked to both processing modules and provided appropriate power sources, NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca is capable of calculating and implementing advanced thaumaturgical workings. These operations were designed to control the axial rotation of rogue asteroid 8837 London[[footnote]] First observed in 1856 by Sir George Biddell Airy, 8837 London is 2.4 kilometers in diameter and orbits 1.95-2.5 astronomical units (AU) from our sun, in the Main Belt between Mars and Jupiter. [[/footnote]] via ectoplasmic manipulation, creating artificial gravity appropriate for human habitation. For more information, see **PSYCHE Historical Records**.

[[size large]]**Rules of Engagement:**[[/size]]

Pursuant to the Kitchener Accords of 1953, NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca will remain in the custody of the Global Occult Coalition. Both processing modules will be disassembled and placed in adjacent storage when not in use.

In the event that 8837 London requires axial adjustment, NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca will be reassembled, integrated with an Everhart Resonator, and given time to calculate the parameters of corrective working. These formulae will be handed over to the International Center for the Study of Unified Thaumatology (ICSUT), who will implement the working using [[[scp-2176|ectoplasm]]] sourced from a vendor of record.

If NTE-2858 diverges from the above parameters, the Resonator should be powered down immediately. If the Resonator cannot be powered down by conventional means, NTE-2858 will be temporarily re-designated **ARL: ##red|2## (Sub Moderate Threat, Physical Response)** until such time that the situation is resolved.

[[div style="border-bottom:2px solid #777; margin-bottom:1px;"]]
[[/div]]
[[div style="border-bottom:1px solid #777;"]]
[[/div]]

+ PSYCHE Historical Records

The following files represent the GOC's historical intelligence regarding NTE-2858-Cyan-Blaecca prior to 1945. Over the past seventy years, these documents were transferred between several institutions; as a result, many records are missing, degraded, or incomplete.
[[include component:image-block
| name=airy.jpg
| caption=Sir George Biddell Airy, 1883.
| width=30%
| align=right]]

++ Origin
Before 1909, matters related to anomalous research, diplomacy and containment in the British Empire were handled by a loose network of Crown corporations and appointees. One such official was Sir George Biddell Airy (1801-1892), an English mathematician who served as Astronomer Royal between 1835 and 1881. In this capacity, Sir Airy managed the Royal Observatory at Greenwich, London, established the Greenwich Meridian as a global reference point, and negotiated human colonization of asteroid 8837 London.

Following his death in 1892, many of Sir Airy's papers were mistakenly divided among his heirs. The files below were recovered by the Crown and transferred to the King's Archives between 1912 and 1914.

[[div class="paper"]]
**//Journal entry regarding observations at Greenwich, dated 1856.//**

My good friend Llywelyn visited me at the Observatory this evening! With a twinkle in his eye, he asked me to take up the equatorial telescope, for he had quite a sight to show me. Indeed, he guided me to a celestial body hitherto unknown: a diamond palace in the heavens, where fair folk once held court.

I found his claim quite astonishing. If anyone were to bridge such vast distances and build such marvels, whyever would they surrender them? Llywelyn explained that the heavens were quite inhospitable. Before long, the novelty of weightlessness wore thin, and besides a single collection of books and baubles, his clan abandoned it completely.

Seeing that I was quite taken with this story, Llywelyn offered me the opportunity to give this astral body a proper English name. The choice seemed obvious. After all, we stand at the heart of the British Empire, in a Royal Observatory funded by the grace and wisdom of the Crown! Humbled by this great legacy, I have named the asteroid "London", and intend to report as much to Her Royal Highness Queen Victoria forthwith.
[[/div]]

[[div class="paper"]]
**//Official copy of the Astronomer's letter to Charles Babbage, 1862.//**

My dear Mister Babbage,

It has been quite some time since we had reason for correspondence. I pray that our past disagreement regarding the utility of mechanical calculators does not weigh heavily on your mind. In fact, I write to you today in the hopes that we can set our history aside and combine our resources towards solving a unique problem.

Today, I spoke with His Royal Highness Albert Edward, Prince of Wales[[footnote]] Crowned King Edward VII in 1901. [[/footnote]], who impressed upon me his concern for loyal subjects in British North America. During his 1860 visit to Ottawa, the Prince met several families dedicated to the Unity of the Empire.[[footnote]] Referring to United Empire Loyalists, a faction of British colonials who fled the United States after the American Revolution and settled in Canadian provinces. [[/footnote]] Speaking in strictest confidence, these men expressed fears that the Americans would seek reprisals for the razing of their White House in 1814; naturally, the Prince assured them that Britain is fully committed to the defense of her colonies.

This past week, the Prince received a letter reiterating these concerns, further citing the instability of colonial government, animosity between English Protestants and French Catholics, and the [[[scp-2750|brutal conquest of Western territories]]] by the American Secure Containment Initiative. He showed me this letter during our meeting, and I confess that the situation seems quite dire.

My colleague has proposed a novel solution: bridging the grand spaces between England, the Province of Canada, and a remote asteroid I named "London", thus furnishing the colonists with a secure redoubt. According to my good friend Llywelyn, such a thing could be accomplished by opening a Way in the metaphysical shadow of our London Bridge, then linking it to an equivalent structure in Canada and an ancient fey bridge on the asteroid. Since the structure has been abandoned these many centuries, there are no observers who could dispute our new name for the metaphysical territory.

Anchoring this Way will require considerable time and aetheric energy. However, our greatest problem is //gravity//. The asteroid cannot sustain its own gravitation. To create a habitable environment, we must create rotational gravity via centrifugal force.

I have calculated the approximate size and density of 8837 London, but manipulating the asteroid from afar is currently beyond our means. We must devise a method for balancing this equation. In truth, I doubt that your machines will be up to the challenge, but I understand that you are eager for an opportunity to prove me wrong. Suffice it to say that if you can help us solve this problem, the Crown may reconsider funding your calculators.

Yours very truly,
Sir George Biddell Airy, KCB
[[/div]]

[[div class="paper"]]
Sir Airy:

I read your recent letter with considerable astonishment. After so many years of silence, //you// come to //me// with a problem? To affect the gravitation of a heavenly body, linked to the busiest bridge in Central London? That is bold indeed! Consider my interest piqued, so long as you are willing to fund this grand endeavor.

Bear in mind that the work has progressed a great deal since last we spoke. Soon, the calculators you so despise shall be made obsolete by the mighty analytical engine, a general-purpose computation platform more precise than any human agent.

To that end, I have formed a very fruitful partnership with the Clockwork Communion Church.[[footnote]] An obscure techno-religious sect formed during the Industrial Revolution. Defunct as of 1953. [[/footnote]] Though most clergymen are unfit for scientific pursuits, there are some men of faith -- like Deacon Bell -- determined to advance civilization through the triumph of industrial arts. His loyal fabricators and lay-brothers are masters of tool-making, possessed of a great Protestant work ethic and fully dedicated to their craft. I have no doubts in their precision. I hope that we can meet to discuss terms very soon.

I am, Sir, yours, etc.,
Charles Babbage
[[/div]]

[[div class="paper"]]
Most splendid. I am pleased to hear it.

Mind, I must apologize for my previous laxity of speech. Our Way shall be centered on the //other// London bridge: Blackfriars. A contractor has already been selected to build a similar wrought-iron crossing over the Thames River in Canada.

G.B.H., KCB
[[/div]]

[[div class="paper"]]
**//Official copy of the Astronomer's letter to Llywelyn y Bychan, dated June 30, 1864.//**

Yet again, Mr. Babbage is wasting time on petty grievances. Rather than building his precious calculators, Charles is publicly campaigning against organ-grinders and idle children. During yesterday's debates in the House of Commons, Sir Shelley disparaged him by name! This will not do.

My friend, I must call upon your particular talents. Please impress upon Mr. Babbage the importance of finishing this project, in no uncertain terms.

[[/div]]

[[div class="paper"]]
**//Excerpted from the Astronomer's letter to Prince Albert Edward, 1871.//**

Your Royal Highness,

I understand and appreciate your concerns regarding the Other London Bridge. Rest assured that Deacon Bell and his engineers are quite capable of finishing the key mechanical components, despite Mr. Babbage's recent passing. In fact, I am quite confident that he will be more useful to us in death than he ever was in life.
[[/div]]

------

++ Development

Starting in 1909, paranatural affairs in the United Kingdom and Crown colonies were handled by the British Occult Service (BOS, or "MI666"). This included the administration of Other London. Records from this era are scarce, but PSYCHE Division has recovered a 1921 briefing packet addressed to higher echelons of BOS bureaucracy.

[[div class="mi666"]]
[[=]]
[[span style="font-size: 2.5em; font-weight: bold; color: #dd6161;"]]CLASSIFIED: MOST SECRET[[/span]]
[[span style="font-size: 1.3em; color: darkgrey;"]]OFFICE OF THE CHIEF OF OCCULT INTELLIGENCE[[/span]]
[[span style="font-size: 1.3em;"]]Executive Briefing on "Other London"[[/span]]
[[/=]]

------
**__HISTORY__**: Other London Bridge opened in 1875. The first settlers took up residence in a vast cavern, two kilometers wide and five kilometers long; there they carved out a river using thaumaturgy, built up fields with fertile soil, raised houses with imported timber, and paved roads with local stone.
[[include component:image-block
| name=settlement.jpg
| caption=Artist's rendition of Other London, 1877.
| width=30%
| align=right]]
By the end of the Sixth Occult War, Other London was a modest town of 678. Today, Other London has 1,012 residents, plus an additional 150 penal subjects.

**__GEOGRAPHY AND CLIMATE__**:  Local topology is oriented relative to the Other Thames River, which flows from north to south along the inner perimeter of the asteroid. Thus we determine the east and west neighborhoods, respectively known as York (Canadian) and Middlesex (British). Upper-class citizens live on the north end of the colony. Lower-class citizens reside on the south side, closer to their places of work.

Other London's main climate is tuned for short, mild seasons, ranging from lows of 0°C to an average of 10°C and highs of 23°C. Numerous other tunnels and chambers have their own microclimates, some of which are appropriate for agriculture, fungiculture, industrial activity or habitation. For safety and security, these regions are isolated by air-locks.

**__GOVERNMENT__**: The people of Other London are represented by a Town Council. Policies are ratified by the Governor General, who represents the Crown's authority. Since 1909, the office of the Governor General has been held //in absentia// by the Chief of Occult Intelligence.

Civil defense, law enforcement and penal security are all managed by the Other London Garrison, currently commanded by BOS Colonel Royce Campbell.

[[include component:image-block
| name=england.jpg
| caption=Blackfriars Bridge, London, England.
| width=30%
| align=right]]

[[include component:image-block
| name=ontario.jpg
| caption=Blackfriars Bridge, London, Ontario.
| width=30%
| align=right]]

**__INFRASTRUCTURE__**: Other London Bridge is a pocket dimension that links the Blackfriars Bridge on 8837 London with two points on Earth: the Blackfriars Bridge of London, England, and the Blackfriars Bridge of London, Ontario. To traverse the Way, one need only focus on crossing the "other" London Bridge.

The route is scaled for foot traffic, light carriages, and small boats, which pass along each region's respective Thames. Integrated enchantments ensure that mundane observers perceive inter-dimensional traffic as non-anomalous. Witnesses assume that travelers have gone "the other way round", and do not question it further.

The colony is powered by coal, steam, and hydroelectric energy. Illumination systems include arc lights, mercury-vapor lamps, and luminescent thaumaturgical workings. In residential areas, these systems are staged and timed to emulate a terrestrial day-night cycle. Since 1876, every effort has been made to link occupied areas by telephone, providing consistent means of communication throughout the colony.

Other London's critical infrastructure was developed in partnership with the Clockwork Communion Church. Whereas most techno-religious sects are increasingly hostile towards the state, the Communion are generally cooperative and wholly civic-minded. Many cite the example of Deacon Bell, who died in a selfless effort to prevent a boiler explosion in 1917. Since the Deacon's passing, Church members have become more insular, but remain essential to colony maintenance.

**__DEMOGRAPHICS__**: According to the 1921 census, 73% of colonists claim ethnic origins in the British Isles, including Englishmen, Irishmen, Scotsmen and others. 8% of the population are Frenchmen; 4% are German; all other populations are negligible, including Slavs, Jews, and Sidhe refugees.

> **Note**: While most fair folk are reluctant to cross the Other London Bridge due to its wrought-iron construction, two Sidhe families made ingress via the small green door in the Tate Library, which predates human colonization.

**__INDUSTRY AND ECONOMY__**: Mining is the primary industry on 8837 London. The asteroid contains abundant iron, copper, nickel, gold, and platinum, which justify the continued expense of maintaining the colony. In the interest of creating a reliable source of fuel and making the environment more hospitable to Fae colonists, many of these iron deposits have been transmuted into coal. The mnemonic key for this thaumaturgical formula is available upon request.[[footnote]] Paired documentation states that the key is, "Bugger my hole, turn this iron to coal!" [[/footnote]]

Agricultural crops include wheat, coarse grains, potatoes, sugar beets, brassicas, juniper berries, hemp, tobacco, and edible mushrooms. Livestock farming is limited to poultry, sheep and goats. The majority of foodstuffs are distributed within the colony, but there is a brisk trade in local tobacco and spirits with terrestrial vendors.

**__LABOR__**: Maintaining a stable workforce has been one of the greatest challenges of the Other London project. Unions have been legal in both England and Canada since 1872; as a result, the first working-class settlers were empowered to establish unions, councils and guilds.

This took a startling turn in 1907, when Other London Garrison identified a covert trade in seditious literature among union members. Their "discussion groups" featured work by Communist philosopher Karl Marx, Bolshevik provocateur Vladimir Lenin, and anarchist agitators such as Mikhail Bakunin, Peter Kropotkin and Emma Goldman. Based on printer's marks, these documents were imported from England. Once the BOS assumed responsibility for Other London, officers received formal authorization to monitor these groups as potential enemies of the state.

With the outbreak of the Great War, citizens across the British Empire were called upon for military service. This left significant gaps in the workforce, precipitating supply chain crises in Other London, England, and beyond. During this time, many empty positions were reassigned to women and young persons.[[footnote]] Defined under contemporary British law as workers aged 13 to 18 years. [[/footnote]] Facing critical shortages in high-risk sectors, the BOS erected secure barracks in the tunnels and began using penal labor for mining and maintenance.

When static warfare began winding down in 1918, many surplus members of the Royal Engineer tunneling companies were hired on to Other London. These veterans were expected to demonstrate loyalty to King and Country, but in practice, many were disillusioned by the Great War, resentful of the officer class, and amenable to socialist politics. Rather than mitigating the threat, their combined discipline strengthened the unions' ranks.

These developments came to a head in 1919. Inspired by reports of a general strike in the Canadian city of Winnipeg, Manitoba, laborers issued a list of demands, including shorter shifts, increased rations, educational resources for young persons, safety protections for penal laborers, and a moratorium on new excavations, pending full surveys by the Royal Engineers. The Crown rejected this ultimatum, prompting a month-long labor action which was finally broken by BOS thaumaturges.

------

**__LATEST UPDATE__ (1921/SEP/17)**: Yesterday, eleven members of a mining crew were blown into hard vacuum while expanding Shaft Seven. Since the miners adhered to standard safety practices and set up air-locks at regular intervals, the colony is not considered to be in imminent danger.

A coalition of civilians, veterans and prisoners have formed a "Digger's Union" to represent all mine workers. This organization attributed the catastrophe to faulty information from an outdated tunnel survey and subsequently voted to authorize strike action. The rest of Other London's labor factions are expected to follow suit. Col. Campbell is requesting support from the Occult Service, citing the increasing likelihood of retaliatory violence.

[[/div]]
[[div class="mi666"]]
Well, can't have that, can we? Tell the Colonel to hold the line. Cancel all new excavations, task this Digger's Union with tunnel maintenance, and whistle up some more Royal Engineers to conduct an exhaustive survey.

Obviously, Campbell won't be keen on this idea. That old battleaxe will say we're caving to the unions. Perhaps he's right. Frankly, I don't care. The structure is big enough for our purposes. We're trying to maintain a permanent colony, not build a bloody beehive.

Signed,
[[span style="font-size: larger; font-weight: bold; color: green; padding-left: 3%;"]]-- C.[[/span]]
[[/div]]

------

++ Evacuation

With the outbreak of the Seventh Occult War, Other London was deemed a strategic asset by the Allied Occult Initiative (AOI) and assigned the codename "DIAMOND PALACE". Most records from this era were stored aboard the colony, and were presumably subject to the document destruction orders listed below.

[[div class="aoi"]]
[[=]]
[[size large]]**Emergency Session Concerning DIAMOND PALACE**[[/size]]
[[table style="border: none; width: 100%;"]]
[[row]]
[[cell]]
**1943/JULY/23**
[[/cell]]
[[cell style="text-align: right;"]]
**SECURITY CLEARANCE 3**
[[/cell]]
[[/row]]
[[/table]]
[[/=]]
[[div style="border-bottom:2px solid #777; margin-bottom:1px;"]]
[[/div]]
[[div style="border-bottom:1px solid #777;"]]
[[/div]]

The recent "apportation raid" on Three Portlands[[footnote]] The Battle of Portlands, 1943. [[/footnote]] has prompted Allied High Command to re-evaluate the security of anomalous sites such as DIAMOND PALACE (asteroid 8837 London, commonly known as Other London). Since 1939, this Crown colony has been used as a labor camp, training complex and staging area for strategic assets moving between North America and Europe. This includes members of the British Occult Service (BOS), the American Unusual Incidents Unit (UIU) and the Canadian Occult and Supernatural Activities Taskforce (OSAT), all of whom have been involved in the Allied war effort.

Other London was founded on the assumption that its physical isolation would guarantee security from hostile forces. However:

# Operating out of the occupied neighborhood of London in Belgrade, Serbia, Nazi thaumaturges could link an appropriate physical structure with the metaphysical shadow of Other London Bridge, enter DIAMOND PALACE, and seize control of the exit.
# If the Way were compromised in this manner, it would take at least one hour for a conventional radio distress call to reach Earth from DIAMOND PALACE.
# Depending on the scale of this theoretical assault force, it is possible that the Obskuracorps and the Thule Society could capture the station and march directly on Allied territory before we receive word of the initial attack.

With the above considerations in mind, High Command has assembled representatives of the BOS, the UIU, and OSAT to conduct a vote on evacuating DIAMOND PALACE and closing the Way linking the colony with England and Canada.

Proposed priorities are as follows:
# Locate and extract all Allied officers, government personnel, and civilian researchers.
# Destroy any sensitive documents pertaining to Allied activity.
# Retrieve all man-portable paraweapons and anomalous technology. Any assets that cannot be carried by hand should be abandoned or disabled.
# Speed of execution is paramount. All other considerations secondary.

Voting follows:
[[<]]
||~ YEA||= 4||
||~ NAY||= 1||
||~ ABSTAIN||= 2||
[[/<]]
The operation will commence with all due haste.

May the record show that special consultant Llywelyn y Bychan has lodged a formal objection against this decision, stating:

> "There's lads and lasses on that rock!
> You'll get 'em off or suck my ████!"

Note that under the terms of his 1864 contract with the BOS, Llywelyn is compelled to follow the above mission parameters and seal Other London Bridge once the operation is complete.
[[/div]]

[[div class="aoi"]]
[[=]]
[[size large]]**Final Report on DIAMOND PALACE**[[/size]]
[[table style="border: none; width: 100%;"]]
[[row]]
[[cell]]
**1943/JULY/25**
[[/cell]]
[[cell style="text-align: right;"]]
**SECURITY CLEARANCE 3**
[[/cell]]
[[/row]]
[[/table]]
[[/=]]
[[div style="border-bottom:2px solid #777; margin-bottom:1px;"]]
[[/div]]
[[div style="border-bottom:1px solid #777;"]]
[[/div]]

Mission complete. Records destroyed.

DIAMOND PALACE lost.

Llywelyn y Bychan discharged from compulsory service with the BOS.

[[/div]]

[[div style="border-bottom:2px solid #777; margin-bottom:1px;"]]
[[/div]]
[[div style="border-bottom:1px solid #777;"]]
[[/div]]

+ PSYCHE Operational Records
++ First Incursion
+++ PTOLEMY Records
[[div class="goc"]]
[[div class="blockquote"]]
||||~ __Office of the Undersecretary General__||
||~ Sender|| D.C. al Fine||
||~ Recipient||High Command Nexus||
||~ Date || 1946/MAR/01||
||~ Subject|| Parathreat Investigation: Other London||

During the Global Occult Coalition's 1st Session this past January, the Council of 108 stressed the importance of securing any strategic assets lost or improperly decommissioned during the Seventh Occult War. To that end, the Office of the Undersecretary General has opened a Parathreat Investigation into Other London, an asteroid colony formerly administrated by the Allied Occult Initiative and abandoned in 1943.

Asteroid 8837 London has been inaccessible for nearly three years. In the interests of re-opening the pocket dimension known as Other London Bridge, PSYCHE Division has reached out to Fae thaumaturge Llywelyn y Bychan, who helped create the Way in 1875.
[[/div]]
[[/div]]

+++ PHYSICS Records
[[div class="goc"]]
[[div class="blockquote"]]

||~ AT/ST Patrol Report (Debrief)||

**Date:** 1946/MAR/04

**Involved Assessment/Strike Team:**

* AT-744 "Black Devils" -- six-man team of Commonwealth commandos specializing in stealth reconnaissance and night warfare.

* Deputy Ambassador (DA) Llywelyn y Bychan -- Fae thaumaturge, former consultant to the British Occult Service.

**Filing Operative:** "Stabbs" 17672354/744

**Mission (Location/Objective):**

* DA Llywelyn will board the asteroid via the Wanderer's Library, emerging from the Tate Library in York, Other London.

* DA Llywelyn will reopen Other London Bridge, enabling Way travel between England, Canada and 8837 London.

* AT-744 will enter through Blackfriars Bridge, England, rendezvous with DA Llywelyn outside the Tate Library, and secure the scene, in the interests of conducting a preliminary survey.

* All assets extract via Blackfriars England once the objectives are complete.

**Encounter Report/Enemy Description:**

DA Llywelyn entered the Wanderer's Library on schedule. As expected, GOC observers were unable to follow, as the Way rejects most persons affiliated with normalcy protection agencies.

Approximately thirty minutes later, the Other London Bridge opened and AT-744 crossed through by focusing on the alternate Blackfriars Bridge.

Upon arrival, two things became obvious. Firstly, DA Llywelyn was not at the rendezvous point. There was no sign of a struggle, nor any indication of which direction he might have gone.

Secondly, Other London is still occupied. In addition to 28 adults who surrendered themselves into GOC custody, AT-744 identified at least 70 survivors watching the team from the banks of the Other Thames, and from several adjacent structures.

When AT-744 acknowledged the survivors, approximately half of the group broke contact, fleeing along the riverside or retreating deeper into the complex. The rest held their positions and addressed the Strike Team in vernacular English:

> Six virgins, eh? How're you gettin' on?  

> You all Goofies? Maries? ...Englishmen?
> 
> (Members of AT-744 identify themselves as Canadian, Irish and Scots, respectively.)
> 
> Ah! Donnie, Mickie and Pete! The whole show!

> **Adolescent:** I'm hungry. (addressing AT-744) You bring coal?
> **Teenager:** No, they're no angels. (shouting) Just a bunch of cabbages!

When AT-744 entered projectile range, survivors began throwing stones, empty cans and glass bottles.

**Results:** Rather than escalating the situation, AT-744 elected to fall back through Other London Bridge. Twenty-eight survivors have been handed over to PSYCHE Division Special Observers for debriefing.

AT-744 reports that crossing Other London Bridge can cause severe disorientation. While standing in the pocket dimension, all three Londons are visible at once, making it difficult to track one's relative position. As such, AT-744 recommends all infantrymen look down at their feet while traversing the Way.

**Personnel Condition:** No injuries.

**Conclusions/Recommendations:** DA Llywelyn y Bychan declared missing in action (MIA).
[[/div]]
[[/div]]

+++ Debrief Summary

[[div class="goc"]]
[[div class="blockquote"]]
||||~ __PSYCHE Division__||
||~ Sender||PSYCHE Division||
||~ Recipient||High Command||
||~ Date ||1946/APR/09||
||~ Subject||Summary of Civilian Debriefings||

All 28 survivors in GOC custody describe themselves as "Maries": loyal citizens of Empire. All exhibit degrees of chronic fatigue, malnutrition, vitamin C and D deficiencies, and osteoporosis, which are reportedly common among the populace. Otherwise, they are in good spirits and eager to reintegrate with society.

The loyalists report more than 1,200 survivors in Other London. Roughly 85% are baseline humans. 5% have adopted Mekhanist prostheses, either out of faith or in hopes of limiting their biological needs. Less than 2% are anomalous prisoners of war (Type Blues and Greens) formerly incarcerated by the Allied Occult Initiative. The remaining 8% are anomalous humanoids, animals, and entities of uncertain classification.

As a result of the evacuation and the subsequent collapse of medical support, Other London's age demographics are dramatically skewed. 35% are children, age 14 and below; 40% are young adults, ages 15-24; the remaining 25% are adults and seniors.

Unsurprisingly, this population is quite unruly. However, the settlement has not descended into total chaos. Instead, once Other London was sealed off, rioters began expropriating "loot" from upper-class neighborhoods. Since cash and precious minerals depreciated overnight, looters focused their attentions on the necessities of life, such as food and clean water. Rather than hoarding these resources, the populace elected to share them in kind.

As time went on and rescue did not appear, colonists began to squabble amongst themselves. Loyalist "Maries" argued that survivors should adhere to the principles of responsible government, whereas "Angels" supported multiple tendencies of Communist, socialist and anarchist thought. The latter majority won out and formed a People's Council to represent the residents, trade organizations and special-interest groups. Loyalists held seats on this People's Council, but their relationship with leftist factions remained tense. Apparently, the remaining residents of Other London are openly resentful of the Allied powers who abandoned the colony in 1943.

Only one person saw DA Llywelyn y Bychan prior to AT-744's arrival. During debrief, Martin Tilford stated:

[[div class="blockquote"]]
Yes, I saw that little man! He skipped out the front doors of the library, clicked his heels and started to sing. I remember just what he said, too.

"What ho, friend! Rescue is near! Round up your mates and get the heck outta here! Step up and skedaddle! I'll issue the Knock, re-open the Bridge and summon the GOC!"

I don't know what happened after that. I was just happy to see you lot.
[[/div]]

DA Llywelyn remains MIA.
[[/div]]
[[/div]]

